There Should Be No Place on the Federal Reserve for Stephen Moore Stephen Moore was interviewed on CNBC this morning. The interview basically centered on Moore making the case for his appointment to the Federal Reserve.

From my perch Stephen Moore's nomination should be immediately rescinded for the following reasons: * Moore's economic beliefs have been inconsistent while his economic forecasts have been consistently wrong-footed. * In listening to the CNBC interview, the Fed nominee is

clearly willing to change policy based on political expediency. * Moore's writings demonstrate a considerable degree of inappropriate misogyny. * That contempt has no place on the Fed or in our society. * He doesn't appreciate the independence of the Federal Reserve.

On @realmoney Shorting Bonds I placed short iShares 20+ Year Treasury Bond ETF (TLT) on my Best Ideas List on June 29, 2016 at $139.55. Back in June, 2016 I predicted in Barron's and in my Diary that we were witnessing a Generational Bottom in Yields -

and I still believe this to be the case. At that time, the yield on the 10 year U.S. note was under 1.40% (compared to 2.525% currently). Today's 10 year yield is down nearly 60 basis points from a 3.10% yield in October, 2018.

From my perch, the low absolute and real yield is a function of global economic concerns, lower-than-expected inflation (and inflationary expectations), a still generous central bank community and current demographic trends, among other issues.

Despite my lower-than-consensus view of global economic growth I am reestablishing my bond short (TLT $123.60) for the following reasons: * Assuming a reduced relationship between the 10 year U.S. note yield and nominal U.S. GDP of 0.7x (vs. the last five to six decades

at a 1.0x multiplier), the bond market is forecasting that real U.S. GDP growth falls well below even my pessimistic expectations. * I expect we are at a bottom in inflation (and in inflationary expectations). (1)The monetary largesse currently being delivered is likely going

to ultimately give way to rising inflation and the emergence of "bond vigilantes." (2) After a sharp decline in oil prices in 4Q2018 that filtered into the inflation stats in 1Q2019, oil has since rebounded. In particular, gasoline prices have rallied sharply and the average

price of a gallon is less than a dime from its highest level since 2014 according to AAA. (3) While there is currently no product inflation, there is, arguably, rampant asset inflation due to aggressive monetary stimulation and the low interest rates that the policy produces.

(4) A near all-time high in the S&P Index gives the Fed no reason whatsoever to consider any further easing. (5) The closer we get to the November, 2020 election, the more likely the Fed sits out a rate cut. (6) Inflation under 2%? Unless you want to eat!

* Fed Chairman Jay Powell was clear in his press conference that they are not worried about the recent drop in PCE because they see other inflation gauges, like the Dallas Fed's trimmed mean that is closer to 2%. Regardless of which one is more accurate, Powell made it clear
